SIMPLE: guess
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Guess
<hw>Guess</hw> <pr>(g⟦ecr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Guessed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Guessing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>gessen</ets>;
akin to Dan. <ets>gisse</ets>, Sw. <ets>gissa</ets>, Icel.
<ets>gizha</ets>, D. <ets>gissen</ets>: cf. Dan. <ets>giette</ets> to
guess, Icel. <ets>geta</ets> to get, to guess. Probably originally, to
try to get, and akin to E. <ets>get</ets>. See <er>Get</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To form an opinion concerning, without knowledge or
means of knowledge; to judge of at random; to conjecture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>First, if thou canst, the harder reason <qex>guess</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To judge or form an opinion of, from reasons that
seem preponderating, but are not decisive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We may then <qex>guess</qex> how far it was from his design.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of ambushed men, whom, by their arms and dress,⟦br⟧
To be Taxallan enemies I <qex>guess</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To solve by a correct conjecture; to conjecture
rightly; <as>as, he who <ex>guesses</ex> the riddle shall have the ring;
he has <ex>guessed</ex> my designs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hit upon or reproduce by memory.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell me their words, as near as thou canst <qex>guess</qex>
them.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To think; to suppose; to believe; to imagine; --
followed by an objective clause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not all together; better far, I <qex>guess</qex>,⟦br⟧
That we do make our entrance several ways.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But in known images of life I <qex>guess</qex>⟦br⟧
The labor greater.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To conjecture; suppose; surmise; suspect; divine;
think; imagine; fancy.</syn> <usage> -- <er>To Guess</er>,
<er>Think</er>, <er>Reckon</er>. <xex>Guess</xex> denotes, to attempt to
hit upon at random; <as>as, to <ex>guess</ex> at a thing when
blindfolded; to conjecture or form an opinion on hidden or very slight
grounds: as, to <ex>guess</ex> a riddle; to <ex>guess</ex> out the
meaning of an obscure passage</as>. The use of the word <ex>guess</ex>
for think or believe, although abundantly sanctioned by good English
authors, is now regarded as antiquated and objectionable by
discriminating writers. It may properly be branded as a colloguialism
and vulgarism when used respecting a purpose or a thing about which
there is no uncertainty; <as>as, I <ex>guess</ex> I 'll go to
bed</as>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guess</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Guess
<hw>Guess</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a guess or random
judgment; to conjecture; -- with at, about, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the place, as well as I may <qex>guess</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guess</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Guess
<hw>Guess</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An opinion as to anything, formed
without sufficient or decisive evidence or grounds; an attempt to hit
upon the truth by a random judgment; a conjecture; a surmise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A poet must confess⟦br⟧
His art 's like physic -- but a happy <qex>guess</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guessable</ent>⟦br⟧
